e/docs/workflows/code-coverage-improvement.md:7:dynamic-access workflows target calls that require reachability metadata,\nforge/docs/workflows/code-coverage-improvement.md:9:executed code has no dynamic-access signal.\nforge/docs/workflows/code-coverage-improvement.md:13:The workflow exists because dynamic-access coverage can rise while ordinary\nforge/docs/workflows/code-coverage-improvement.md:14:library code coverage remains weak. A test suite can exercise enough\nforge/docs/workflows/code-coverage-improvement.md:21:usage across the library, not only the calls that appear in a dynamic-access\nforge/docs/workflows/code-coverage-improvement.md:31:produced a passing test suite, but its own work product is broader API coverage\nforge/docs/workflows/code-coverage-improvement.md:35:tests used to generate or validate reachability metadata. Code coverage tests\nforge/docs/workflows/code-coverage-improvement.md:37:exist to exercise dynamic-access behavior and validate native-image metadata.\nforge/docs/workflows/code-coverage-improvement.md:39:locations, metrics, and publication evidence so improving broad API coverage\nforge/docs/workflows/code-coverage-improvement.md:40:does not change the meaning of metadata-generation coverage.\nforge/docs/workflows/code-coverage-improvement.md:42:This workflow must not replace dynamic-access generation. It complements it:\nforge/docs/workflows/code-coverage-improvement.md:45:- Code coverage improvement answers whether tests exercise the wider library\nforge/docs/workflows/code-coverage-improvement.md:61:addresses or dynamic-access call sites. Examples include untested public\nforge/docs/workflows/code-coverage-improvement.md:69:(§GOAL-maximize-library-coverage).\nforge/docs/workflows/code-coverage-improvement.md:91:A code coverage improvement run is successful only when all of these hold:\nforge/docs/workflows/code-coverage-improvement.md:95:- The generated tests are written to the separate code coverage suite, not to\nforge/docs/workflows/code-coverage-improvement.md:100:- Existing dynamic-access coverage, metadata validity, and JVM/native test\nforge/docs/workflows/code-coverage-improvement.md:120:(§WF-code-coverage-improvement-architecture).\nforge/docs/workflows/code-coverage-improvement.md:122:# WF-code-coverage-improvement-architecture: Code coverage improvement workflow architecture\nforge/docs/workflows/code-coverage-improvement.md:124:Code coverage improvement (§WF-code-coverage-improvement) should be implemented\nforge/docs/workflows/code-coverage-improvement.md:126:evidence differ from dynamic-access coverage. The workflow reuses Forge's\nforge/docs/workflows/code-coverage-improvement.md:137:  test suite, separate code coverage test suite, strategy, metrics root, source\nforge/docs/workflows/code-coverage-improvement.md:148:  and failed API coverage targets for chunked or resumed runs.\nforge/docs/workflows/code-coverage-improvement.md:157:workflows iterate over uncovered dynamic-access classes and calls; code\nforge/docs/workflows/code-coverage-improvement.md:158:coverage improvement iterates over API and behavior targets selected from the\nforge/docs/workflows/code-coverage-improvement.md:159:inventory/profile join (§WF-dynamic-access-workflow).\nforge/docs/workflows/code-coverage-improvement.md:161:The code coverage test suite should be physically and logically separate from\nforge/docs/workflows/code-coverage-improvement.md:163:metadata-generation tests as context, but generated coverage tests must be\nforge/docs/workflows/code-coverage-improvement.md:164:written to the coverage-suite root and measured with code-coverage metrics.\nforge/docs/workflows/code-coverage-improvement.md:165:Metadata-generation tests remain the source of dynamic-access and native-image\nforge/docs/workflows/code-coverage-improvement.md:180:operational shape as chunked dynamic-access exhaust state without sharing the\nforge/docs/workflows/code-coverage-improvement.md:181:dynamic-access report schema (§WF-dynamic-access-exhaust-report).\nforge/docs/workflows/code-coverage-improvement.md:194:- Did the run preserve existing dynamic-access, metadata, JVM, and native-image\nforge/docs/workflows/code-coverage-improvement.md:210:- selected API coverage targets and their terminal statuses\nforge/docs/workflows/code-coverage-improvement.md:217:evidence from dynamic-access coverage evidence. A PR that improves code\nforge/docs/workflows/code-coverage-improvement.md:218:coverage should not be presented as a dynamic-access coverage fix unless it\nforge/docs/workflows/code-coverage-improvement.md:219:also ran and reported the dynamic-access workflow (§WF-improve-library-coverage).\nforge/docs/workflows/code-coverage-improvement.md:225:inventory builder, a coverage analyzer, a target-state schema, metrics support,\nforge/docs/strategies.md:38:  `dynamic-access-iteration`).\nforge/docs/strategies.md:62:§WF-forge-workflow-architecture), including the dynamic-access strategy family\nforge/docs/strategies.md:63:defined in §WF-dynamic-access-strategy-family that shares this loader.\nforge/docs/strategies.md:97:`dynamic_access_iterative` (§WF-dynamic-access-workflow),\nforge/docs/strategies.md:98:`optimistic_dynamic_access`, `increase_dynamic_access_coverage`\nforge/docs/strategies.md:99:(§WF-improve-library-coverage), `javac_iterative`, and `java_run_iterative`\nforge/docs/strategies.md:108:`optimistic_dynamic_access` workflow (§WF-improve-library-coverage), the `pi`\nforge/docs/strategies.md:110:`optimistic-dynamic-access-iteration` prompt, and parameters for optimistic\nforge/docs/strategies.md:117:the version-bump failure and then improve dynamic-access coverage use the\nforge/docs/strategies.md:118:`increase_dynamic_access_coverage` workflow (§WF-improve-library-coverage) as\nforge/docs/strategies.md:120:`javac_iterative` for compilation-failure issues and `java_run_iterative` for\nforge/docs/strategies.md:121:JVM runtime-failure issues; after that primary workflow succeeds, the composite\nforge/docs/strategies.md:122:workflow engine runs the dynamic-access coverage phase defined by\nforge/docs/strategies.md:123:§WF-dynamic-access-workflow. The concrete bundle names, prompt template paths,\nforge/docs/strategies.md:131:set `max-test-iterations` and `source-context-types`. Per-class dynamic-access\nforge/docs/strategies.md:133:`source-context-types`. Optimistic dynamic-access bundles set\nforge/docs/strategies.md:138:§WF-native-test-verification-callers. Composite coverage bundles combine the\nforge/docs/strategies.md:139:primary workflow's limits with dynamic-access limits so the selected primary\nforge/docs/strategies.md:140:workflow can run first and the coverage phase\nforge/docs/strategies.md:141:(§WF-improve-library-coverage) can run afterward.\nforge/docs/workflows/native-image-run-fix.md:17:native-image failure proves that the existing test is invalid for the bumped\nforge/docs/workflows/native-image-run-fix.md:46:    Metadata -- no --> Fail[Return failure]\nforge/docs/workflows/native-image-run-fix.md:93:Java fail-fix and dynamic-access workflows. When metrics are added, they must\nforge/docs/workflows/architecture.md:15:fallback §WF-basic-iterative), dynamic-access generation\nforge/docs/workflows/architecture.md:16:(§WF-dynamic-access-workflow), Java failure repair\nforge/docs/workflows/architecture.md:19:(§WF-native-metadata-tracing), dynamic-access coverage improvement\nforge/docs/workflows/architecture.md:20:(§WF-improve-library-coverage), and planned code coverage improvement\nforge/docs/workflows/architecture.md:21:(§WF-code-coverage-improvement).\nforge/docs/workflows/architecture.md:36:are used for that run. Shared utilities provide source context, dynamic-access\nforge/docs/workflows/architecture.md:47:layer (§ORCH-forge-orchestration-spec). The planned code coverage workflow\nforge/docs/workflows/architecture.md:48:follows the same split (§WF-code-coverage-improvement-architecture).\nforge/docs/workflows/architecture.md:57:cycles, local gate interpretation, retry budgets, failure handoff, metrics\nforge/docs/workflows/architecture.md:101:example, retry budgets, source-context selections, dynamic-access limits, and\n./skills/review-library-update-request/SKILL.md:3:description: Review pull requests with the `library-update-request` label in graalvm-reachability-metadata. Use when asked to review or triage a PR that updates metadata/tests for an existing library version, especially generated PRs titled like `[GenAI] Improve coverage for group:artifact:version using gpt-5.5`. Focus on preserving dynamic-access coverage percentage between versions, verifying reporter-requested metadata is present and exercised by tests, and applying the relevant test/scope rules from new-library reviews without requiring a minimum new-library dynamic-access coverage threshold.\n./skills/review-library-update-request/SKILL.md:8:These PRs update support for an existing library version. Review them as existing-library updates: the target library is already supported, so the PR must preserve coverage quality while adding any metadata or tests requested by the linked issue.\n./skills/review-library-update-request/SKILL.md:16:- Dynamic-access coverage percentage must not drop between the previously supported version and the requested version unless the PR gives a concrete, credible reason. Compare the percentage/ratio only; do not block because the absolute covered or total call count changed.\n./skills/review-library-update-request/SKILL.md:17:- Do not require `library-new-request`'s minimum dynamic-access threshold. A library update can be acceptable with low coverage if the percentage did not regress and the requested issue work is covered.\n./skills/review-library-update-request/SKILL.md:55:4. Check dynamic-access coverage percentage.\n./skills/review-library-update-request/SKILL.md:59:   - Use `versions[0].dynamicAccess.coverageRatio` or the equivalent ratio shown in the PR description.\n./skills/review-library-update-request/SKILL.md:60:   - Compare the top-level dynamic-access percentage/ratio. Do not require covered call counts or total call counts to match, and do not block just because one version has fewer dynamic-access calls.\n./skills/review-library-update-request/SKILL.md:61:   - A lower coverage percentage for the requested version is blocking unless the PR gives a concrete explanation, such as upstream removal of reachable dynamic-access sites or an intentionally narrower supported surface.\n./skills/review-library-update-request/SKILL.md:64:   - Do not apply the `library-new-request` rule that dynamic-access coverage must be above 20%.\n./skills/review-library-update-request/SKILL.md:68:   - It is acceptable to inspect metadata entries for this issue-requested metadata check. Avoid broader entry-by-entry review beyond the reporter request unless there is a concrete failure.\n./skills/review-library-update-request/SKILL.md:76:   - If the issue request is ambiguous, ask for a concrete explanation in the PR and ensure the tests cover the most plausible reporter-described failure path.\n./skills/review-library-update-request/SKILL.md:89:   - If CI is flaky but the diff, issue-requested metadata, and coverage comparison are sound, ask for a rerun instead of blocking on speculation.\n./skills/review-library-update-request/SKILL.md:96:- Dynamic-access coverage percentage did not drop between the previous version and requested version, or any drop is convincingly explained by an upstream surface change.\n./skills/review-library-update-request/SKILL.md:104:- Dynamic-access coverage percentage drops without a credible explanation.\n./skills/review-library-update-request/SKILL.md:107:- Tests use direct reflection, no-op class literals, or direct resource checks to fake requested-metadata coverage.\n./skills/review-library-update-request/SKILL.md:115:- The linked issue request is ambiguous and the PR needs a short explanation tying metadata and tests to the reporter's failure.\n./skills/review-library-update-request/SKILL.md:122:- For coverage percentage drops: say that `library-update-request` PRs must not reduce dynamic-access coverage percentage between versions, cite old and new percentages, and ask for restored coverage or a concrete explanation.\n./skills/review-library-update-request/SKILL.md:125:- For fake requested-metadata coverage: say direct reflection/class literals/direct resource lookup prove only the test code, not the library path that needs metadata.\n./skills/review-library-update-request/SKILL.md:127:- For unverified `catch (Error)`: say dynamic class loading tests should verify Native Image failures with `NativeImageSupport.isUnsupportedFeatureError(e)` and re-throw any other error.\n./skills/review-library-update-request/SKILL.md:136:- Bad issue-requested metadata coverage with direct reflection:\n./skills/review-library-update-request/SKILL.md:147:- Better issue-requested metadata coverage through public API:\n./skills/review-library-update-request/SKILL.md:161:- Bad resource coverage with direct lookup only:\n./skills/review-library-update-request/SKILL.md:173:- Better resource coverage through library initialization:\nforge/docs/workflows/java-fail-fix.md:10:covers two version-bump failure modes:\nforge/docs/workflows/java-fail-fix.md:12:- **Compilation failure** — `compileJava` or `compileTestJava` fails because the\nforge/docs/workflows/java-fail-fix.md:14:- **Runtime test failure** — compilation succeeds, but the Gradle `test` task\nforge/docs/workflows/java-fail-fix.md:20:makes the test compile and pass, and then improve dynamic-access coverage for\nforge/docs/workflows/java-fail-fix.md:21:the new version through the composite phase (§WF-improve-library-coverage). The\nforge/docs/workflows/java-fail-fix.md:26:A repaired test must keep meaningful functional coverage; the workflow must not\nforge/docs/workflows/java-fail-fix.md:72:- `--javac`: `javac_iterative_with_coverage_sources_pi_gpt-5.4`\nforge/docs/workflows/java-fail-fix.md:73:- `--java-run`: `java_run_iterative_with_coverage_sources_pi_gpt-5.4`\nforge/docs/workflows/java-fail-fix.md:97:    Failed2 -- budget exhausted --> Fail[Return failure]\nforge/docs/workflows/java-fail-fix.md:99:    Failed -- nativeTest or none --> Coverage[Composite dynamic-access<br/>coverage phase]\nforge/docs/workflows/java-fail-fix.md:108:   and capture a checkpoint commit so failure handling can tell setup output\nforge/docs/workflows/java-fail-fix.md:110:2. Run `./gradlew test -Pcoordinates=<library>` to collect failure output.\nforge/docs/workflows/java-fail-fix.md:113:4. Loop: rerun `./gradlew test` and send subsequent failure output back to the\nforge/docs/workflows/java-fail-fix.md:116:6. After the JVM fix succeeds, run the dynamic-access coverage phase for the new\nforge/docs/workflows/java-fail-fix.md:118:   the new version better covered (§WF-improve-library-coverage,\nforge/docs/workflows/java-fail-fix.md:123:wording: javac fixes use compilation-failure wording and write\nforge/docs/workflows/java-fail-fix.md:124:`fix_javac_fail.json`; java-run fixes use runtime-failure wording and write\nforge/docs/workflows/java-fail-fix.md:130:When a runtime failure occurs under `nativeTest`, the common cause is missing\nforge/docs/workflows/java-fail-fix.md:141:It is the same component the dynamic-access workflow drives per class, here\nforge/docs/workflows/java-fail-fix.md:152:- Improved dynamic-access coverage for the new version from the composite phase\nforge/docs/workflows/java-fail-fix.md:153:  (§WF-improve-library-coverage).\nforge/docs/workflows/java-fail-fix.md:154:- Durable logs for the initial Gradle run, each agent turn, the coverage phase,\nforge/docs/workflows/java-fail-fix.md:218:- Fix the runtime test failures for library version `{updated_library}`. Test was initially written for version `{old_version}`.\nforge/docs/workflows/java-fail-fix.md:226:- Look for API changes, including renamed methods, changed signatures, removed classes, changed behavior, or new exceptions that explain the runtime failures.\nforge/docs/workflows/java-fail-fix.md:227:- Stop inspecting sources once you understand the cause of each failure. Then make the minimal edit.\nforge/docs/workflows/java-fail-fix.md:231:- Test that is fixed must maintain functional coverage. Never simplify the test to the point of triviality.\nforge/docs/workflows/java-fail-fix.md:242:`forge_metadata.py` dispatches Java version-bump failures through the unified\n./skills/fix-index-file-inconsistencies/SKILL.md:19:tested versions that belong before the next metadata entry. Common failures:\nforge/docs/workflows/dynamic-access.md:1:# WF-dynamic-access-workflow: Dynamic-access workflow specification\nforge/docs/workflows/dynamic-access.md:3:The dynamic-access workflow is part of the Forge workflow system\nforge/docs/workflows/dynamic-access.md:8:The dynamic-access workflow family generates or improves JUnit/Kotlin/Scala\nforge/docs/workflows/dynamic-access.md:9:tests for a target library so that **dynamic-access call sites** reported by\nforge/docs/workflows/dynamic-access.md:10:the reachability repo's coverage tool are exercised at runtime. Coverage of\nforge/docs/workflows/dynamic-access.md:14:class-by-class refinement (§GOAL-maximize-library-coverage).\nforge/docs/workflows/dynamic-access.md:16:### WF-dynamic-access-strategy-family: Dynamic-access strategy family\nforge/docs/workflows/dynamic-access.md:18:Forge currently has three registered dynamic-access workflow engines:\nforge/docs/workflows/dynamic-access.md:22:| `dynamic_access_iterative` | Per-class dynamic-access generation or refinement. It selects one uncovered class at a time, prompts with that class's remaining call sites, verifies coverage deltas, and commits resolved or partially resolved class progress (§WF-dynamic-access-iterative-strategy). | `dynamic_access_*`, `library_update_pi_gpt-5.5` |\nforge/docs/workflows/dynamic-access.md:23:| `optimistic_dynamic_