.md:15:Chunked dynamic-access runs publish their parts incrementally\nforge/docs/git-scripts.md:35:native-run-fix, and coverage-improvement publishers each know which paths are\nforge/docs/git-scripts.md:55:### New library support and coverage improvement\nforge/docs/git-scripts.md:58:`make_pr_improve_coverage.py` (`library-update-request`). Both report the agent\nforge/docs/git-scripts.md:60:token counts; iteration count; library-coverage and generated lines-of-code\nforge/docs/git-scripts.md:61:metrics; metadata-entry counts; and dynamic-access coverage with its supporting\nforge/docs/git-scripts.md:66:diverge, while coverage improvement reports a before/after stats diff computed\nforge/docs/git-scripts.md:85:omits them. It reports the previous and new library-coverage percentages, a\nforge/docs/git-scripts.md:117:## GIT-chunked-linking: Chunked dynamic-access PR linking\nforge/docs/git-scripts.md:119:Chunked dynamic-access PRs must use `Refs: #<issue>` until the final chunk;\nforge/docs/git-scripts.md:121:§WF-chunked-dynamic-access-pr-linking. This keeps the backing issue open\nforge/docs/git-scripts.md:124:reprocessing classes (§WF-dynamic-access-exhaust-report).\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:3:description: Review pull requests with the `fixes-java-run-fail` label in graalvm-reachability-metadata. Use when asked to review or triage a PR described as `fixes-java-run-fail` or one that fixes Java/JVM runtime test failures for an existing library version update. Focus on validating the Java runtime fix, keeping the diff scoped, and ensuring dynamic-access coverage does not drop between the previously tested version and the new version.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:9:These PRs repair tests, dependencies, or narrow runtime setup after an existing library version compiles, but the JVM-based test fails when it runs. Review them more lightly than `library-new-request` PRs: the library already exists, so the goal is to restore Java runtime behavior for the new version while preserving meaningful test and dynamic-access coverage.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:17:- Be more relaxed than `library-new-request`: do not reject only because a test resembles older coverage, stays in an existing package layout, or contains compatibility branches for multiple supported versions.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:18:- Do not accept changes that remove meaningful test coverage just to make `java` pass.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:20:- Treat dynamic-access coverage preservation as the main quality gate. The new version should not report lower dynamic-access coverage than the previously tested version unless the PR gives a concrete, credible reason.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:21:- For numeric gates, compare the reported evidence as-is. Do not inspect generation filters, agent configuration, or metadata contents to second-guess why dynamic-access or metadata-count numbers are what they are.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:50:   - Confirm the edit addresses the actual JVM runtime failure, such as changed runtime behavior, missing test resources, service loading changes, dependency conflicts, classpath/module issues, initialization order, changed exception types, or changed API semantics that only fail during execution.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:56:4. Check dynamic-access coverage across versions.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:58:   - Compare `dynamicAccess.coverageRatio`, `coveredCalls`, `totalCalls`, and the `dynamicAccess.breakdown` entries for reflection, resources, proxies, serialization, JNI, or any other present report type.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:59:   - Do not use `user-code-filter.json`, agent configuration, or metadata file contents to argue that the reported dynamic-access values are not comparable. Use the stats values as reported unless the stats are missing or stale.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:60:   - A lower `coverageRatio` or lower `coveredCalls` for the new version is blocking unless the total dynamic-access surface changed and the PR explains why the reduction is expected.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:61:   - If `totalCalls` increases while `coveredCalls` stays flat or the ratio drops, ask for additional test coverage or metadata unless the uncovered calls are clearly outside the library behavior under test.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:69:   - Do not require an exact match. Differences are normal when upstream APIs move, generated metadata is cleaned up, or dynamic-access totals change.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:71:   - When the new total is below 25% of the original and the tests and dynamic-access stats still claim comparable coverage, ask for restored metadata or a concrete explanation of the API/runtime-surface change.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:77:   - Prefer seeing the full target `test` lane green because a Java runtime fix can still reduce native-image coverage.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:78:   - If current-defaults and future-defaults lanes both run, both should pass unless the PR clearly targets only one failing lane and the other failure is unrelated infrastructure noise.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:79:   - If CI is flaky but the diff and coverage comparison are sound, ask for a rerun instead of blocking on speculation.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:85:- The PR is scoped to the target existing library and the Java runtime failure it fixes.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:87:- Dynamic-access coverage does not drop between the previous and new tested versions, or any apparent drop is convincingly explained by a changed upstream API/runtime surface.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:95:- Dynamic-access coverage drops without a credible explanation and replacement coverage.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:97:- CI failures indicate the Java runtime problem is not actually fixed.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:103:- The API or runtime behavior change is plausible but the PR does not explain why a coverage drop is expected.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:110:- For coverage drops: say that dynamic-access coverage must not regress between tested versions, cite the old and new values, and ask for either restored coverage or a concrete explanation.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:112:- For deleted or bypassed coverage: say that the PR fixes Java runtime execution by removing coverage and should instead adapt the test to the new runtime behavior.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:113:- For swallowed exceptions: say that catching or ignoring the failing exception hides the runtime failure instead of proving the library behavior works.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:114:- For native skips that does not depend on the open-ended dynamic class loading: say that the PR avoids the failing native path instead of fixing it, so it does not demonstrate native-image runtime coverage.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:115:- For unverified `catch (Error)`: say that dynamic class loading tests should verify Native Image failures with `NativeImageSupport.isUnsupportedFeatureError(e)` and re-throw any other error.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:125:- Bad runtime repair that swallows the failure:\n./skills/review-library-new-request/SKILL.md:21:- Require reported dynamic-access coverage above 20% when there are dynamic-access calls to cover. Use the exploded stats files under `stats/<group>/<artifact>/<metadata-version>/stats.json` when available, and block the PR when dynamic-access coverage is 20% or lower or the PR provides no credible dynamic-access coverage evidence for non-zero dynamic-access calls.\n./skills/review-library-new-request/SKILL.md:22:- Treat dynamic-access coverage counts as a minimum gate, not complete metadata evidence. They can miss metadata required through downstream libraries, so do not use high coverage alone to prove that the submitted metadata is complete or necessary.\n./skills/review-library-new-request/SKILL.md:23:- Treat `0/0` dynamic-access coverage as a valid no-calls case, not as failed coverage. Do not reject a PR only because the exploded stats report `0/0` dynamic-access calls while the PR adds metadata; those stats can miss metadata required through downstream libraries.\n./skills/review-library-new-request/SKILL.md:24:- Do not explicitly read or review individual metadata entries. Use the metadata entry count reported in the PR description for the metadata/dynamic-access mismatch check; do not manually count entries from metadata files. When the PR reports both library metadata entries and test-only metadata entries, use their sum as the PR-reported metadata entry count. Only request investigation when the covered dynamic-access call count is at least 75% higher than that PR-reported total.\n./skills/review-library-new-request/SKILL.md:57:   - For metadata/dynamic-access mismatch checks, use only the metadata entry count reported in the PR description, such as `Metadata entries`, or legacy fields such as `Entries` and `Entries found` in older PRs; add `Test-only metadata entries` when the PR reports it; do not manually count metadata entries from files.\n./skills/review-library-new-request/SKILL.md:61:5. Compare the PR claims, test, and reported coverage as one unit.\n./skills/review-library-new-request/SKILL.md:62:   - If the PR claims specific coverage numbers that do not line up with the diff, ask for investigation.\n./skills/review-library-new-request/SKILL.md:63:   - Confirm reported dynamic-access coverage is above 20% when the stats include dynamic-access calls.\n./skills/review-library-new-request/SKILL.md:64:   - If the PR reports zero dynamic-access calls and `reachability-metadata.json` is `{}`, that is acceptable as long as the test is library-specific and the scope is otherwise correct.\n./skills/review-library-new-request/SKILL.md:65:   - If the PR reports zero dynamic-access calls while adding metadata, do not reject it on that basis alone; dynamic-access stats can miss metadata required through downstream libraries.\n./skills/review-library-new-request/SKILL.md:66:   - If the stats report 20% coverage or lower for non-zero dynamic-access calls, or no usable coverage signal for claimed dynamic-access behavior, ask for stronger tests or refreshed coverage evidence.\n./skills/review-library-new-request/SKILL.md:67:   - Ask for metadata/coverage mismatch investigation only when the covered dynamic-access call count is at least 75% higher than the PR-reported metadata entry count, where the reported count is `Metadata entries` plus `Test-only metadata entries` when both are present. For older PRs, use legacy `Entries` or `Entries found` as the metadata entry count.\n./skills/review-library-new-request/SKILL.md:90:  - Reported dynamic-access coverage is 20% or lower for non-zero dynamic-access calls, absent for claimed dynamic-access behavior, or not credible from the diff.\n./skills/review-library-new-request/SKILL.md:97:- For native skips that does not depend on the open-ended dynamic class loading: say that the PR avoids the failing native path instead of fixing it, so it does not demonstrate native-image runtime coverage.\n./skills/review-library-new-request/SKILL.md:98:- For unverified `catch (Error)`: say that dynamic class loading tests should verify Native Image failures with `NativeImageSupport.isUnsupportedFeatureError(e)` and re-throw any other error.\n./skills/review-library-new-request/SKILL.md:101:- For insufficient dynamic-access coverage: say that new-library PRs need dynamic-access coverage above 20% when there are dynamic-access calls to cover, and ask for stronger tests or refreshed coverage evidence.\n./skills/review-library-new-request/SKILL.md:102:- For unsupported coverage claims: ask for refreshed coverage evidence when the PR makes concrete coverage claims that are not supported by the diff.\n./skills/review-library-new-request/SKILL.md:103:- For metadata/dynamic-access entry mismatch: ask for investigation only when covered dynamic-access calls are at least 75% higher than the PR-reported metadata entry count, summing library and test-only metadata entries when both are reported. Do not manually count or argue from metadata contents.\n./COVERAGE.md:5:![Coverage over Time](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/oracle/graalvm-reachability-metadata/stats/coverage/latest/metrics-over-time.svg#gh-light-mode-only)\n./COVERAGE.md:6:![Coverage over Time](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/oracle/graalvm-reachability-metadata/stats/coverage/latest/metrics-over-time-dark.svg#gh-dark-mode-only)\n./COVERAGE.md:10:| Library | Versions | Description | Dynamic access coverage |\n./COVERAGE.md:189:| `com.google.guava:failureaccess` | [1.0.1<br>- 1.0.3](metadata/com.google.guava/failureaccess/index.json) | <details><summary>Show</summary> failureaccess provides Guava's internal classes for optionally exposing the cause of a failed Future through a fast path. It includes InternalFutureFailureAccess and InternalFutures for lightweight failure-cause access used by Guava concurrency utilities.</details> | [100.0% (0/0 calls)](stats/com.google.guava/failureaccess/) |\n./COVERAGE.md:204:| `com.google.truth:truth` | [1.1.3<br>- 1.4.5](metadata/com.google.truth/truth/index.json) | <details><summary>Show</summary> Truth is a Java assertion framework that provides fluent assertions and readable failure messages for tests. It includes built-in subjects for common JDK and Guava types and extension points for defining custom assertions.</details> | [100.0% (8/8 calls)](stats/com.google.truth/truth/) |\n./COVERAGE.md:268:| `com.softwaremill.sttp.tapir:tapir-server_3` | [1.11.25<br>- 1.12.6](metadata/com.softwaremill.sttp.tapir/tapir-server_3/index.json) | <details><summary>Show</summary> Tapir is a Scala library for describing HTTP API endpoints as type-safe values that can be interpreted as servers, clients, and OpenAPI, AsyncAPI, or JSON Schema documentation. The tapir-server module provides the core server-side interpreter, request and response model, interceptors, decode-failure handling, CORS support, metrics hooks, and logging abstractions used by Tapir server backends.</details> | [100.0% (0/0 calls)](stats/com.softwaremill.sttp.tapir/tapir-server_3/) |\n./COVERAGE.md:332:| `dev.failsafe:failsafe` | [3.3.1<br>- 3.3.2](metadata/dev.failsafe/failsafe/index.json) | <details><summary>Show</summary> Failsafe is a Java library for handling transient failures with resilience patterns such as retries, circuit breakers, timeouts, bulkheads, rate limiters, and fallbacks. It lets applications compose synchronous and asynchronous execution policies around operations so failures can be handled consistently.</details> | [100.0% (0/0 calls)](stats/dev.failsafe/failsafe/) |\n./COVERAGE.md:364:| `io.arrow-kt:arrow-autoclose-jvm` | [2.2.2<br>- 2.2.3](metadata/io.arrow-kt/arrow-autoclose-jvm/index.json) | <details><summary>Show</summary> Arrow AutoCloseable provides a Kotlin DSL for acquiring AutoCloseable resources and registering finalizers that run when the scope exits. It closes resources in reverse order, propagates failures with suppressed exceptions, and avoids closing on fatal JVM errors.</details> | [100.0% (0/0 calls)](stats/io.arrow-kt/arrow-autoclose-jvm/) |\n./COVERAGE.md:407:| `io.github.resilience4j:resilience4j-bulkhead` | [2.3.0<br>- 2.4.0](metadata/io.github.resilience4j/resilience4j-bulkhead/index.json) | <details><summary>Show</summary> Resilience4j Bulkhead provides semaphore- and thread-pool-based bulkhead implementations that limit concurrent calls to protected code. It helps isolate failures and prevent one overloaded dependency or code path from exhausting resources needed by the rest of a JVM application.</details> | [100.0% (0/0 calls)](stats/io.github.resilience4j/resilience4j-bulkhead/) |\n./COVERAGE.md:408:| `io.github.resilience4j:resilience4j-circuitbreaker` | [2.3.0<br>- 2.4.0](metadata/io.github.resilience4j/resilience4j-circuitbreaker/index.json) | <details><summary>Show</summary> Resilience4j CircuitBreaker provides a lightweight Java implementation of the circuit breaker pattern for guarding calls to unreliable dependencies. It tracks call outcomes and latency, transitions between closed, open, and half-open states, and can be configured with failure-rate, slow-call, wait-duration, and permitted-call thresholds.</details> | [100.0% (0/0 calls)](stats/io.github.resilience4j/resilience4j-circuitbreaker/) |\n./COVERAGE.md:456:| `io.kotest:kotest-assertions-shared-jvm` | [6.1.11](metadata/io.kotest/kotest-assertions-shared-jvm/index.json) | <details><summary>Show</summary> Kotest assertions shared JVM provides common assertion primitives, matcher contracts, and error collection support used by Kotest assertion modules on the JVM. It supplies reusable infrastructure for building fluent Kotlin test assertions and reporting assertion failures.</details> | [100.0% (0/0 calls)](stats/io.kotest/kotest-assertions-shared-jvm/) |\n./COVERAGE.md:819:| `org.apache.maven.plugins:maven-surefire-plugin` | [2.22.2](metadata/org.apache.maven.plugins/maven-surefire-plugin/index.json) | <details><summary>Show</summary> The Maven Surefire Plugin runs a Maven project's unit tests during the test phase and reports the results. It integrates test providers such as JUnit, TestNG, and POJO-based tests with Maven's lifecycle, including options for filtering, forking, and failure handling.</details> | [100.0% (1/1 calls)](stats/org.apache.maven.plugins/maven-surefire-plugin/) |\n./COVERAGE.md:1230:| `org.scalameta:munit-diff_3` | [1.2.4<br>- 1.3.2](metadata/org.scalameta/munit-diff_3/index.json) | <details><summary>Show</summary> MUnit Diff provides Scala diffing utilities used by MUnit to compare values and render actionable assertion failures. The Scala 3 JVM artifact includes unified diff algorithms, patch data structures, equality helpers, and console printers for producing readable test failure output.</details> | [100.0% (0/0 calls)](stats/org.scalameta/munit-diff_3/) |\n./COVERAGE.md:1231:| `org.scalameta:munit_3` | [0.7.29<br>- 1.3.2](metadata/org.scalameta/munit_3/index.json) | <details><summary>Show</summary> MUnit is a Scala testing framework that provides suites, assertions, fixtures, and test discovery through JUnit-compatible runners. The Scala 3 artifact publishes the core JVM test framework for Scala 3 projects, letting build tools run synchronous and asynchronous Scala tests with useful diffing and failure reporting.</details> | [100.0% (2/2 calls)](stats/org.scalameta/munit_3/) |\n./COVERAGE.md:1237:| `org.scalatest:scalatest-diagrams_3` | [3.2.19<br>- 3.3.0-alpha.2](metadata/org.scalatest/scalatest-diagrams_3/index.json) | <details><summary>Show</summary> ScalaTest Diagrams adds diagrammed assertion support to ScalaTest, showing evaluated subexpressions when an assertion fails. The Scala 3 artifact provides the org.scalatest.diagrams APIs and macros for writing ScalaTest assertions whose failure messages include expression diagrams.</details> | [100.0% (0/0 calls)](stats/org.scalatest/scalatest-diagrams_3/) |\n./COVERAGE.md:1257:| `org.scoverage:scalac-scoverage-runtime_2.13` | [1.4.1<br>- 2.5.2](metadata/org.scoverage/scalac-scoverage-runtime_2.13/index.json) | <details><summary>Show</summary> scalac-scoverage-runtime provides the runtime support used by the scoverage Scala compiler plugin to record coverage measurements from instrumented Scala code. It writes and reads invoked statement identifiers so scoverage can calculate statement and branch coverage after tests run.</details> | [100.0% (0/0 calls)](stats/org.scoverage/scalac-scoverage-runtime_2.13/) |\n./COVERAGE.md:1395:| `software.amazon.awssdk:retries` | [2.34.0<br>- 2.46.5](metadata/software.amazon.awssdk/retries/index.json) | <details><summary>Show</summary> This module provides the AWS SDK for Java 2.x retry strategy implementations, including standard, legacy, and adaptive retry behavior. It classifies retryable failures, computes backoff delays, and manages retry token and circuit-breaker state used by AWS SDK clients.</details> | [100.0% (0/0 calls)](stats/software.amazon.awssdk/retries/) |\n./COVERAGE.md:1396:| `software.amazon.awssdk:retries-spi` | [2.34.0<br>- 2.46.5](metadata/software.amazon.awssdk/retries-spi/index.json) | <details><summary>Show</summary> AWS SDK for Java retries-spi defines the retry strategy service-provider interfaces and request/response contracts used by SDK clients. It includes retry token handling and backoff strategy APIs so callers and SDK internals can classify retryable failures, compute retry delays, and coordinate retry capacity.</details> | [100.0% (0/0 calls)](stats/software.amazon.awssdk/retries-spi/) |\n./build.gradle:357: * indicating success or failure.\n./build.gradle:418: * per-command logs under build/command-logs and aggregating failures.\n./build.gradle:438:    def failures = Collections.synchronizedList(new ArrayList<Map>())\n./build.gradle:447:                failures.add([label: label, logFile: logFile, exit: exit])\n./build.gradle:456:    if (!failures.isEmpty()) {\n./build.gradle:458:        failures.each { f ->\n./build.gradle:462:        failures.each { f ->\n./stats/org.awaitility/awaitility/4.2.1/stats.json:7:          \"coverageRatio\" : 1.0,\n./stats/org.awaitility/awaitility/4.2.1/stats.json:12:      \"coverageRatio\" : 1.0,\n./stats/org.awaitility/awaitility/4.2.1/execution-metrics.json:8:    \"strategy_name\": \"java_run_iterative_with_coverage_sources_pi_gpt-5.5\",\n./stats/org.awaitility/awaitility/4.2.1/execution-metrics.json:17:            \"coverageRatio\": 1.0,\n./st